<div class="entrycontent">When I built my current <a href="http://www.chaosreigns.com/dancer/">gaming / htpc</a> computer almost a year ago one of the reasons I put off buying a new drive was reports that <a href="http://www.google.com/search?q=perpendicular recording">perpendicular recording</a> was coming.  <br /><br />"...linear hard disk recordings max out at 100 to 200 Gb/inÂ².  Perpendicular recording is expected to increase the amount of available storage space to up to 5-10 times that..."<br /><br /><a name="cutid1"></a>In this time <a href="http://www.silentpcreview.com">Silent PC Review</a> (which I used extensively in building this machine) has added one 500gb hd to their recommended list (continuing their trend of only recommending one hd over 100gb).  It is the <a href="http://www.silentpcreview.com/article617-page1.html">Western Digital Caviar SE16 WD5000KS</a>, apparently the only line of hard drives anybody has tried to make quiet.<br /><br />If you search <a href="http://www.newegg.com/">newegg</a> for "perpendicular" you find 18 Seagate drives and 1 Hitachi.  The 500GB Seagate Barracuda 7200.10 is a close comparison to thee WD Caviar SE16.  It costs 1.3x as much and even on a cost per performance basis doesn't look at all worthwhile.  <br /><br />So while I'm glad perpendicular recording exists as a useful development path, it doesn't look like it's going to have any terribly sudden results.<br /><br />So I ordered the Western Digital.  I figure I'll back some stuff up on DVD, and other stuff up on my existing 250GB Western Digital Caviar.<a name='cutid1-end'></a></div>

